ps://i.imgur.com/GOdwZr6.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/Bb0Jkdi</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[DingerGold]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Adding gold foil to this thread was satisfying. Can't wait to price it out</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/tdhZGVp</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/mOut6YK.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This is probably my lowest effort post. Nice to see my printshop supplies were not wasted.
https://www.instagram.com/tfoust10/</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/tdhZGVp</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[tfoust10]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Land Back!</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/mbkgx1g</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/nD2I81S.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>https://abcnews.go.com/Lifestyle/wireStory/california-redwood-forest-returned-native-american-tribes-82473730</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/mbkgx1g</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[mydamnkidsdontthinkimfunny]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>This is why we can't have nice things.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/on3GK0w</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ZGgjy8G.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Youtube is truly a wretched hive of scum an villainy. 

Todays example comes in the form of a "restoration" channel, that usually does bladed weaponry - knives, swords etc. 

Their particular claim to fame is lying about the items they restore (calling replicas "antique") and performing destructive modifications, while calling them "restorations".

As expected, their unskilled, dishonest work has paid off, to the tune of 5 million subscribers.

I've previously covered their "work" here: https://imgur.com/gallery/zVR4zyp</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/Z8sNv3h.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Martini variants. The martini rifle system was first adopted in 1871, went through many changes (and had many different subvariants, like carbines for artillery).

I believe the rifle abused in this video was one of the carbine variants of the martini enfield, based on barrel length and barrel calibre.

Image source https://www.rockislandauction.com/detail/1028/366/five-single-shot-martini-pattern-longarms</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/lqw3c2T.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>So, onto todays reckless video: What do you do if an antique martini rifle, one with shallow and minimal rust? 

Well, I can tell you "carefully restore it via carding and skilled gunsmithing" is apparently *not* the answer.

(Rifles are outside my field, cant say if its a martini henry, martini metford, martini enfield etc, nor which revision it is)</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/JnX3nNq.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Wood appears to be in rough shape, but by no means unrecoverable. Still has the regimental disk in the stock.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/hJ8tvny.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Some markings, IIRC the broad arrow is a mark of the British war office. Commonly seen on all government firearms.

Again, very shallow corrosion. This is well within the realms of restoration and conservation.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/HZIbYEq.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Spoiler alert, things go badly from here. 

Oh, and that text overlay? That's from the original video. Incase anyone thought this was an innocent mistake...</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/3v7BL6T.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Can anyone guess why the barrel might be coming off? Perhaps to convert away that shallow corrosion and check the condition of the rifling?</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/62LXjUp.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Ah, of course not. The only logical thing to do with an antique rifle, is turn it into a shitty replica sword. I wonder how well it will adhere to the traditional design of a "katana"?</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/FLciQtT.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>The angle grinder, my favorite restoration tool. Definitely not destructive at all. Who cares about preserving the finite and limited number of historical artifacts out there, anyway?</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/HgowTQ0.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Definitely not something you could have used standard bar stock or scrap steel to make, is it. Clearly you *need* to molest an antique rifle if you want some steel to make into a sword blade.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/dU1zkNu.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Now, call me crazy but that curvature looks rather wrong for a katana. Maybe a particularly deeply curved tachi, but even then...</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/bg10nCH.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>And what's this? A leather covered tsuka? Where is the samegawa, the stingray skin? If you're already destroying history, I guess why not shit all over traditional materials used in katana, too.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/dEsIfpn.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This is a samegawa wrapped tsuka. This is how it should look. 

Image from https://www.cottontailcustoms.com/tsukamaki/ - which contains a very detailed guide on how to do this whole process correctly. Which they obviously did not bother to google.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/zGDdyZ8.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>I guess alternating ito wrap is too much to expect from a content farm. Why bother doing things correctly, it's clear your viewers don't care about history, accuracy or authenticity.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/EuQDZ7g.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Alternating ito. How it should be done.

Again, from https://www.cottontailcustoms.com/tsukamaki/</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/oebD5FU.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>And how it looks done right: tight, even diamonds, alternating directions between each rung of the wrapping, nice nodules of stingray skin underneath.

